5":"1390–1465","1389–Male":"1389–Deceased","1394–1423":"1394–1423","1421–1466":"1421–1466","1423–1506":"1423–1506","1358–1413":"1358–1413","1362–Female":"1362–Deceased","1362":"1362","1394":"1394","1390":"1390","after 1423":"after 1423","1413":"1413","1358":"1358","1423":"1423","1455":"1455","1466":"1466","1389":"1389","Abt. 1413":"about 1413","1421":"1421","1465":"1465","1506":"1506","Walton. Lancashire, England":"Walton on the Hill, Northumbria, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","of Walton, Lancs., Eng.":"Walton on the Hill, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Woodcock","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","from Middle English <i>wodecok</i> ‘woodcock’ (Old English <i>wuducocc</i>, a compound of Old English <i>wudu</i> ‘wood’ + <i>cocc</i> ‘cock, bird’), a type of bird that is notoriously easy to catch. Therefore, the name might have been either for a person who caught or sold woodcock, or a nickname for a gullible person.","in some cases, because there can be confusion between <i>-cock</i> and <i>-cot</i> in surnames, and therefore the name may also be a variant of <b>Woodcott</b>, a habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>wudu</i> ‘wood’ + <i>cot</i> ‘cottage, shelter’, such as Woodcott in Cheshire and Hampshire or Woodcote in Hampshire, Surrey, Oxfordshire, Warwickshire, and Shropshire, or from any residence at a cottage in or near a wood."],"variants":[{"name":"Woodcox","meanings":["English: variant of   Woodcock  ."]}]},{"name":"Seth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name (from a Hebrew word meaning ‘appointed, placed’), borne by the third son of Adam, who was born after the murder of Abel (Genesis 4:25, ‘And Adam knew his wife again; and she bare a son, and called his name Seth: For God, said she, hath appointed me another seed instead of Abel, whom Cain slew’). It is recorded in England from the 1400s and was popular among the Puritans (particularly for children born after the death of an elder sibling). By the 20th century it had become rare. It was used for the darkly passionate rural character Seth Starkadder in  Stella Gibbons's  satirical novel Cold Comfort Farm (  1932 ), and has recently enjoyed a revival ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":65,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Seth Woodcock was born in 1390, in Walton on the Hill, Northumbria, England, his father, Robert Woodcock, was 33 and his mother, Mrs. Robert Woodcock, was 29. He had at least 2 sons with Mrs. Seth Woodcock. He died in 1465, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 75."},"et":{"1390–1465":"1390–1465","1389–Male":"1389–Surnud","1394–1423":"1394–1423","1421–1466":"1421–1466","1423–1506":"1423–1506","1358–1413":"1358–1413","1362–Female":"1362–Surnud","1362":"1362","1394":"1394","1390":"1390","after 1423":"pärast 1423","1413":"1413","1358":"1358","1423":"1423","1455":"1455","1466":"1466","1389":"1389","Abt. 1413":"umbes 1413","1421":"1421","1465":"1465","1506":"1506","Walton. Lancashire, England":"Walton on the Hill, Northumbria, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","of Walton, Lancs., Eng.":"Walton on the Hill, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1390–1465":"1390–1465","1389–Male":"1389–K